# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: self-stabilization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] A **Byzantine fault** is a condition of a system, particularly a distributed computing system, where a fault occurs such that different symptoms are presented to different observers, including imperfect information on whether a system component has failed.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine fault is also known as a **Byzantine generals problem**, a **Byzantine agreement problem**, or a **Byzantine failure**.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine fault is any fault presenting different symptoms to different observers.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine failure is the loss of a system service due to a Byzantine fault in systems that require consensus among multiple components.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The Byzantine allegory considers a number of generals who are attacking a fortress.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The generals must decide as a group whether to attack or retreat; some may prefer to attack, while others prefer to retreat.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The important thing is that all generals agree on a common decision, for a half-hearted attack by a few generals would become a rout, and would be worse than either a coordinated attack or a coordinated retreat.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The problem is complicated by the presence of treacherous generals who may not only cast a vote for a suboptimal strategy; they may do so selectively.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] For instance, if nine generals are voting, four of whom support attacking while four others are in favor of retreat, the ninth general may send a vote of retreat to those generals in favor of retreat, and a vote of attack to the rest.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Those who received a retreat vote from the ninth general will retreat, while the rest will attack (which may not go well for the attackers).
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The problem is complicated further by the generals being physically separated and having to send their votes via messengers who may fail to deliver votes or may forge false votes.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Without message signing, Byzantine fault tolerance can only be achieved if the total number of generals is greater than three times the number of disloyal (faulty) generals.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] There can be a default vote value given to missing messages.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] For example, missing messages can be given a "null" value.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Further, if the agreement is that the null votes are in the majority, a pre-assigned default strategy can be used (e.g., retreat).
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The typical mapping of this allegory onto computer systems is that the computers are the generals and their digital communication system links are the messengers.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Although the problem is formulated in the allegory as a decision-making and security problem, in electronics, it cannot be solved by cryptographic digital signatures alone, because failures such as incorrect voltages can propagate through the encryption process.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Thus, a faulty message could be sent such that some recipients detect the message as faulty (bad signature), others see it is having a good signature, and a third group also sees a good signature but with different message contents than the second group.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The problem of obtaining Byzantine consensus was conceived and formalized by Robert Shostak, who dubbed it the *interactive consistency* problem.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] This work was done in 1978 in the context of the NASA-sponsored SIFT project in the Computer Science Lab at SRI International.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] SIFT (for Software Implemented Fault Tolerance) was the brainchild of John Wensley, and was based on the idea of using multiple general-purpose computers that would communicate through pairwise messaging in order to reach a consensus, even if some of the computers were faulty.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] At the beginning of the project, it was not clear how many computers in total were needed to guarantee that a conspiracy of *n* faulty computers could not "thwart" the efforts of the correctly-operating ones to reach consensus.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Shostak showed that a minimum of 3*n+*1 are needed, and devised a two-round 3*n+1* messaging protocol that would work for *n*=1.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] His colleague Marshall Pease generalized the algorithm for any n > 0, proving that 3*n*+1 is both necessary and sufficient.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] These results, together with a later proof by Leslie Lamport of the sufficiency of 3*n* using digital signatures, were published in the seminal paper, *Reaching Agreement in the Presence of Faults.* The authors were awarded the 2005 Edsger W.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] To make the interactive consistency problem easier to understand, Lamport devised a colorful allegory in which a group of army generals formulate a plan for attacking a city.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] In its original version, the story cast the generals as commanders of the Albanian army.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The name was changed, eventually settling on "Byzantine", at the suggestion of Jack Goldberg to future-proof any potential offense-giving.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] This formulation of the problem, together with some additional results, were presented by the same authors in their 1982 paper, "The Byzantine Generals Problem".
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The objective of Byzantine fault tolerance is to be able to defend against failures of system components with or without symptoms that prevent other components of the system from reaching an agreement among themselves, where such an agreement is needed for the correct operation of the system.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The remaining operationally correct components of a Byzantine fault tolerant system will be able to continue providing the system's service as originally intended, assuming there are a sufficient number of accurately-operating components to maintain the service.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] When considering failure propagation only via errors, Byzantine failures are considered the most general and most difficult class of failures among the failure modes.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The so-called fail-stop failure mode occupies the simplest end of the spectrum.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Thus, Byzantine failures can confuse failure detection systems, which makes fault tolerance difficult.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Despite the allegory, a Byzantine failure is not necessarily a security problem involving hostile human interference: it can arise purely from physical or software faults.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] This kind of fault tolerance does not encompass the correctness of the value itself; for example, an adversarial component that deliberately sends an incorrect value, but sends that same value consistently to all components, will not be caught in the Byzantine fault tolerance scheme.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Several early solutions were described by Lamport, Shostak, and Pease in 1982.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] There are many systems that claim BFT without meeting the above minimum requirements (e.g., blockchain).
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Given that there is mathematical proof that this is impossible, these claims need to include a caveat that their definition of BFT strays from the original.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] That is, systems such as blockchain don't guarantee agreement.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] They use resource-intensive mechanisms that make disagreements impractical to maintain.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Several system architectures were designed c.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] 1980 that implemented Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] These include: Draper's FTMP, Honeywell's MMFCS, and SRI's SIFT.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] In 1999, Miguel Castro and Barbara Liskov introduced the "Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance" (PBFT) algorithm, which provides high-performance Byzantine state machine replication, processing thousands of requests per second with sub-millisecond increases in latency.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] After PBFT, several BFT protocols were introduced to improve its robustness and performance.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] For instance, Q/U, HQ, Zyzzyva, and ABsTRACTs, addressed the performance and cost issues; whereas other protocols, like Aardvark and RBFT, addressed its robustness issues.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Furthermore, Adapt tried to make use of existing BFT protocols, through switching between them in an adaptive way, to improve system robustness and performance as the underlying conditions change.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Furthermore, BFT protocols were introduced that leverage trusted components to reduce the number of replicas, e.g., A2M-PBFT-EA and MinBFT.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Recent research addresses the scalability limits of traditional BFT implementations (which often incur $O(n^{2})$ communication complexity) by parallelizing consensus.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] For example, the Cerberus protocol maps data to a large, fixed state space to couple consensus instances with specific transaction sets.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] This allows BFT processes to run independently in parallel, enabling linear scalability relative to the network size.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Several examples of Byzantine failures that have occurred are given in two equivalent journal papers.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] These and other examples are described on the NASA DASHlink web pages.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Byzantine fault tolerance mechanisms use components that repeat an incoming message (or just its signature, which can be reduced to just a single bit of information if self-checking pairs are used for nodes) to other recipients of that incoming message.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] All these mechanisms make the assumption that the act of repeating a message blocks the propagation of Byzantine symptoms.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] For systems that have a high degree of safety or security criticality, these assumptions must be proven to be true to an acceptable level of fault coverage.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] When providing proof through testing, one difficulty is creating a sufficiently wide range of signals with Byzantine symptoms.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Such testing will likely require specialized fault injectors.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Byzantine errors were observed infrequently and at irregular points during endurance testing for the newly constructed *Virginia*-class submarine, at least through 2005 (when the issues were publicly reported).
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The Bitcoin network works in parallel to generate a blockchain with proof of work allowing the system to overcome Byzantine failures and reach a coherent global view of the system's state.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Some proof of stake blockchains also use BFT algorithms.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Byzantine fault tolerance is a crucial concept in blockchain technology, ensuring that a network can continue to function even when some nodes (participants) fail or act maliciously.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] This tolerance is necessary because blockchains are decentralized systems with no central authority, making it essential to achieve consensus among nodes, even if some try to disrupt the process.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Ensuring that an AI system behaves reliably and as intended, especially in the presence of unexpected faults or adversarial conditions, is a complex challenge.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] By accepting that components may fail, and further that frontier AI models may deceive, Byzantine fault tolerance has been proposed as an approach towards AI safety.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Structuring AI systems as ensembles of AI artifacts or modules that check and balance each other leads to strong assurances that no single errant or deceptive component can easily steer the system into an unsafe state.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] , BFT-based systems are designed to tolerate up to one-third of faulty or malicious nodes without compromising the network's integrity.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] Instead of relying on a central authority, the network's security depends on the ability of honest nodes to outnumber and outmaneuver malicious ones.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] BFT is especially important in private or permissioned blockchains, where a limited number of known participants need to reach a consensus quickly and securely.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] These networks often use BFT protocols to enhance performance and security.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] For example, SAFEbus can achieve Byzantine fault tolerance within the order of a microsecond of added latency.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The SpaceX Dragon considers Byzantine fault tolerance in its design.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The Ares rocket avionics, now the Space Launch System (SLS), utilizes a triplex with an interstage of accomplish Byzantine resilience.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] The Orion spacecraft utilizes self-checking pairs to detect and mask Byzantine faults.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] In legislatures, civil societies, polls, statistical surveys, and so forth, systems that require a minimum supermajority threshold agreement greater than two-thirds are similar to consensus reflective of Byzantine Fault Tolerant -like characteristics.
[src:self-stabilization/byzantine-fault] By contrast, systems that operate on the sub-supermajority basis of simple majorities or a minority government could be vulnerable to Byzantine fault -like behavior.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] In computer science, the **dining philosophers problem** is an example problem often used in concurrent algorithm design to illustrate synchronization issues and techniques for resolving them.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] It was originally formulated in 1965 by Edsger Dijkstra as a student exam exercise, presented in terms of computers competing for access to tape drive peripherals.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Soon after, Tony Hoare gave the problem its present form.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Five philosophers dine together at the same table.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Each philosopher has their own plate at the table.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] There is a fork between each pair of adjacent plates.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The dish served is a kind of spaghetti which has to be eaten with two forks.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Each philosopher can only alternately think and eat.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Moreover, a philosopher can only eat their spaghetti when they have both a left and a right fork.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Thus, two forks will only be available when their two nearest neighbors are thinking, not eating.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] After an individual philosopher finishes eating, they will put down both forks.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The problem is how to design a regimen (a concurrent algorithm) such that any philosopher will not starve; *i.e.*, each can forever continue to alternate between eating and thinking, assuming that no philosopher can know when others may want to eat or think (an issue of incomplete information).
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The problem was designed to illustrate the challenges of avoiding deadlock, a system state in which no progress is possible.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] With these instructions, the situation may arise where each philosopher holds the fork to their left; in that situation, they will all be stuck forever, waiting for the other fork to be available: it is a deadlock.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Resource starvation, mutual exclusion, and livelock are other types of sequence and access problems.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] A solution must negate at least one of those four conditions.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] In practice, negating mutual exclusion or non-preemption somehow can give a valid solution, but most theoretical treatments assume that those assumptions are non-negotiable, instead attacking resource holding or circular waiting (often both).
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Dijkstra's solution negates resource holding; the philosophers atomically pick up both forks or wait, never holding exactly one fork outside of a critical section.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] To accomplish this, Dijkstra's solution uses one mutex, one semaphore per philosopher, and one state variable per philosopher.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] This solution is more complex than the resource hierarchy solution.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] This is a C++20 version of Dijkstra's solution with changes by Andrew S.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The function test() and its use in take_forks() and put_forks() make the Dijkstra solution deadlock-free.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] This solution negates circular waiting by assigning a partial order to the resources (the forks, in this case), and establishes the convention that all resources will be requested in order, and that no two resources unrelated by order will ever be used by a single unit of work at the same time.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Here, the resources (forks) will be numbered 1 through 5, and each unit of work (philosopher) will always pick up the lower-numbered fork first, and then the higher-numbered fork, from among the two forks he plans to use.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The order in which each philosopher puts down the forks does not matter.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] In this case, if four of the five philosophers simultaneously pick up their lower-numbered forks, only the highest-numbered fork will remain on the table, so the fifth philosopher will not be able to pick up any fork.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Moreover, only one philosopher will have access to that highest-numbered fork, so he will be able to eat using two forks.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] This can intuitively be thought of as having one "left-handed" philosopher at the table, who – unlike all the other philosophers – takes his fork from the left first.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] While the resource hierarchy solution avoids deadlocks, it is not always practical, especially when the list of required resources is not completely known in advance.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] For example, if a unit of work holds resources 3 and 5 and then determines it needs resource 2, it must release 5, then 3, before acquiring 2, and then it must re-acquire 3 and 5 in that order.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Computer programs that access large numbers of database records would not run efficiently if they were required to release all higher-numbered records before accessing a new record, making the method impractical for that purpose.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The resource hierarchy solution is not *fair*.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] If philosopher 1 is slow to take a fork, and if philosopher 2 is quick to think and pick their forks back up, then philosopher 1 will never get to pick up both forks.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] A fair solution must guarantee that each philosopher will eventually eat, no matter how slowly that philosopher moves relative to the others.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The following source code is a C++11 implementation of the resource hierarchy solution for five philosophers.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The sleep_for() function simulates the time normally spent with business logic.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Another approach is to guarantee that a philosopher can only pick up both forks or none by introducing an arbitrator to replace circular waiting, e.g., a waiter.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] In order to pick up the forks, a philosopher must ask permission of the waiter.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The waiter gives permission to only one philosopher at a time until the philosopher has picked up both of his forks.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The waiter can be implemented as a mutex.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] A solution presented by William Stallings is to allow a maximum of *n-1* philosophers to sit down at any time.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The last philosopher would have to wait (for example, using a semaphore) for someone to finish dining before he "sits down" and requests access to any fork.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] This negates circular wait, guaranteeing that at least one philosopher may always acquire both forks, allowing the system to make progress.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Misra proposed a different solution to the dining philosophers problem to allow for arbitrary agents (numbered *P*1, ..., *P**n*) to contend for an arbitrary number of resources, unlike Dijkstra's solution.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] It is also completely distributed and requires no central authority after initialization.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] However, it violates the requirement that "the philosophers do not speak to each other" (due to the request messages).
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] When a philosopher wants to use a set of resources (*i.e.*, eat), the said philosopher must obtain the forks from his contending neighbors.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] For all such forks that the philosopher does not have, he sends a request message.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] When a philosopher with a fork receives a request message, he keeps the fork if it is clean, but gives it up when it is dirty.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] If the philosopher sends the fork over, he cleans the fork before doing so.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] After a philosopher is done eating, all his forks become dirty.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] If another philosopher had previously requested one of the forks, the philosopher who has just finished eating cleans the fork and sends it.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] This solution also allows for a large degree of concurrency and will solve an arbitrarily large problem.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] The clean/dirty labels act as a way of giving preference to the most "starved" processes, and a disadvantage to processes that have just "eaten".
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] One could compare their solution to one where philosophers are not allowed to eat twice in a row without letting others use the forks in between.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Chandy and Misra's solution is more flexible than that, but has an element tending in that direction.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] In their analysis, they derive a system of preference levels from the distribution of the forks and their clean/dirty states.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] They show that this system may describe a directed acyclic graph, and if so, the operations in their protocol cannot turn that graph into a cyclic one.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] This guarantees that deadlock cannot occur by negating circular waiting.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] However, if the system is initialized to a perfectly symmetric state, like all philosophers holding their left side forks, then the graph is cyclic at the outset, and their solution cannot prevent a deadlock.
[src:self-stabilization/dining-philosophers-problem] Initializing the system so that philosophers with lower IDs have dirty forks ensures the graph is initially acyclic.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] A **distributed algorithm** is an algorithm designed to run on computer hardware constructed from interconnected processors.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] Distributed algorithms are used in different application areas of distributed computing, such as telecommunications, scientific computing, distributed information processing, and real-time process control.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] Standard problems solved by distributed algorithms include leader election, consensus, distributed search, spanning tree generation, mutual exclusion, and resource allocation.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] Distributed algorithms are a sub-type of parallel algorithm, typically executed concurrently, with separate parts of the algorithm being run simultaneously on independent processors, and having limited information about what the other parts of the algorithm are doing.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] One of the major challenges in developing and implementing distributed algorithms is successfully coordinating the behavior of the independent parts of the algorithm in the face of processor failures and unreliable communications links.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] An atomic commit is an operation where a set of distinct changes is applied as a single operation.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] If the atomic commit succeeds, it means that all the changes have been applied.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] If there is a failure before the atomic commit can be completed, the "commit" is aborted and no changes will be applied.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] Consensus algorithms try to solve the problem of a number of processes agreeing on a common decision.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] More precisely, a Consensus protocol must satisfy the four formal properties below.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] Leader election is the process of designating a single process as the organizer of some task distributed among several computers (nodes).
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] Before the task is begun, all network nodes are unaware of which node will serve as the "leader," or coordinator, of the task.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] After a leader election algorithm has been run, however, each node throughout the network recognizes a particular, unique node as the task leader.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] Reliable broadcast is a communication primitive in distributed systems.
[src:self-stabilization/distributed-algorithm] A reliable broadcast can have sequential, causal or total ordering.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
