[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:self-stabilization/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In distributed computing, **leader election** is the process of designating a single process as the organizer of some task distributed among several computers (nodes).
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Before the task has begun, all network nodes are either unaware which node will serve as the "leader" (or coordinator) of the task, or unable to communicate with the current coordinator.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "leader" state.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Leader election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Many other algorithms have been suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the leader election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The problem of leader election is for each processor eventually to decide whether it is a leader or not, subject to the constraint that exactly one processor decides that it is the leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In every execution, exactly one processor becomes elected and the rest determine that they are not elected.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] **Uniqueness**: there is exactly one processor that considers itself as leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] **Agreement**: all other processors know who the leader is.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] A ring network is a connected-graph topology in which each node is exactly connected to two other nodes, i.e., for a graph with n nodes, there are exactly n edges connecting the nodes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] A ring is said to be anonymous if every processor is identical.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] More formally, the system has the same state machine for every processor.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] There is no deterministic algorithm to elect a leader in anonymous rings, even when the size of the network is known to the processes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] This is due to the fact that there is no possibility of breaking symmetry in an anonymous ring if all processes run at the same speed.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The state of processors after some steps only depends on the initial state of neighbouring nodes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] So, because their states are identical and execute the same procedures, in every round the same messages are sent by each processor.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Therefore, each processor state also changes identically and as a result if one processor is elected as a leader, so are all the others.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] For simplicity, here is a proof in anonymous synchronous rings.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Consider an anonymous ring R with size n>1.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Assume there exists an algorithm "A" to solve leader election in this anonymous ring R.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] of the admissible execution of A in R, all the processes have the same states.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The above lemma contradicts the fact that after some finite number of rounds in an execution of A, one process entered the elected state and other processes entered the non-elected state.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] A common approach to solve the problem of leader election in anonymous rings is the use of probabilistic algorithms.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In such approaches, generally processors assume some identities based on a probabilistic function and communicate it to the rest of the network.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] At the end, through the application of an algorithm, a leader is selected (with high probability).
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Since there is no algorithm for anonymous rings (proved above), the asynchronous rings would be considered as asynchronous non-anonymous rings.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In non-anonymous rings, each process has a unique $id$ , and they don't know the size of the ring.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Leader election in asynchronous rings can be solved by some algorithm with using $O(n^{2})$ messages or $O(n\log n)$ messages.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In the $O(n^{2})$ algorithm, every process sends a message with its $id$ to the left edge.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Then waits until a message from the right edge.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] If the $id$ in the message is greater than its own $id$ , then forwards the message to the left edge; else ignore the message, and does nothing.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] If the $id$ in the message is equal to its own $id$ , then sends a message to the left announcing myself is elected.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Other processes forward the announcement to the left and turn themselves to non-elected.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] It is clear that the upper bound is $O(n^{2})$ for this algorithm.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In the $O(n\log n)$ algorithm, it is running in phases.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] On the k th phase, a process will determine whether it is the winner among the left side $2^{k}$ and right side $2^{k}$ neighbors.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] If it is a winner, then the process can go to next phase.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In phase 0 , each process P needs to determine itself is a winner or not by sending a message with its $id$ to the left and right neighbors (neighbor do not forward the message).
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The neighbor replies an $ACK$ only if the $id$ in the message is larger than the neighbor's $id$ , else replies an $ACK_{fault}$ .
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] If P receives two $ACK$ s, one from the left, one from the right, then P is the winner in phase 0 .
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In phase k , the winners in phase $k-1$ need to send a message with its $id$ to the $2^{k}$ left and $2^{k}$ right neighbors.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] If the neighbors in the path receive the $id$ in the message larger than their $id$ , then forward the message to the next neighbor, otherwise reply an $ACK_{fault}$ .
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] If the $2^{k}$ th neighbor receives the $id$ larger than its $id$ , then sends back an $ACK$ , otherwise replies an $ACK_{fault}$ .
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] If the process receives two $ACK$ s, then it is the winner in phase k .
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In the last phase, the final winner will receive its own $id$ in the message, then terminates and send termination message to the other processes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In the worst case, each phase there are at most ${\frac {n}{2^{k}+1}}$ winners, where k is the phase number.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] There are $\lceil \log(n-1)\rceil$ phases in total.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Each winner sends in the order of $2^{k}$ messages in each phase.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] So, the messages complexity is $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In Attiya and Welch's Distributed Computing book, they described a non-uniform algorithm using $O(n)$ messages in synchronous ring with known ring size n .
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The algorithm is operating in phases, each phase has n rounds, each round is one time unit.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In phase 0 , if there is a process with $id=0$ , then process 0 sends termination message to the other processes (sending termination messages cost n rounds).
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The algorithm will check if there is a phase number equals to a process $id$ , then does the same steps as phase 0 .
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] At the end of the execution, the minimal $id$ will be elected as the leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] It used exactly n messages and $n(minimum\_id+1)$ rounds.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Itai and Rodeh introduced an algorithm for a unidirectional ring with synchronized processes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] They assume the size of the ring (number of nodes) is known to the processes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] For a ring of size n, a≤n processors are active.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Each processor decides with probability of a^(-1) whether to become a candidate.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] At the end of each phase, each processor calculates the number of candidates c and if it is equal to 1, it becomes the leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] To determine the value of c, each candidate sends a token (pebble) at the start of the phase which is passed around the ring, returning after exactly n time units to its sender.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Every processor determines c by counting the number of pebbles which passed through.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] This algorithm achieves leader election with expected message complexity of O(nlogn).
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] A similar approach is also used in which a time-out mechanism is employed to detect deadlocks in the system.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] There are also algorithms for rings of special sizes such as prime size and odd size.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In typical approaches to leader election, the size of the ring is assumed to be known to the processes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In the case of anonymous rings, without using an external entity, it is not possible to elect a leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Even assuming an algorithm exists, the leader could not estimate the size of the ring. i.e. in any anonymous ring, there is a positive probability that an algorithm computes a wrong ring size.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] To overcome this problem, Fisher and Jiang used a so-called leader oracle Ω? that each processor can ask whether there is a unique leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] They show that from some point upward, it is guaranteed to return the same answer to all processes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In one of the early works, Chang and Roberts proposed a uniform algorithm in which a processor with the highest ID is selected as the leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Each processor sends its ID in a clockwise direction.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] A processor receives a message and compares the ID with its own.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] If the ID is bigger than the processor passes it through, otherwise it discards the message.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The authors show that this algorithm uses $O(n^{2})$ messages in the worst case and $O(n\log n)$ in the average case.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Hirschberg and Sinclair improved this algorithm with $O(n\log n)$ message complexity by introducing a bidirectional message-passing scheme.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The mesh is another popular form of network topology, especially in parallel systems, redundant memory systems and interconnection networks.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In a mesh structure, nodes are either corner (only two neighbours), border (only three neighbours) or interior (with four neighbours).
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The number of edges in a mesh of size a x b is m=2ab-a-b.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] A typical algorithm to solve the leader election in an unoriented mesh is to only elect one of the four corner nodes as the leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Since the corner nodes might not be aware of the state of other processes, the algorithm should first wake up the corner nodes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] *Election process*: the election in outer ring takes two stages at most with $6(a+b)-16$ messages.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] *Termination*: leader sends a terminating message to all nodes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The message complexity is at most $6(a+b)-16$ , and if the mesh is square-shaped, $O({\sqrt {n}})$ .
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] An oriented mesh is a special case where port numbers are compass labels, i.e. north, south, east and west.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Leader election in an oriented mesh is trivial.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] "north" and "east" and make sure that node knows it is a leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] A special case of mesh architecture is a torus which is a mesh with "wrap-around".
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In this structure, every node has exactly 4 connecting edges.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] One approach to elect a leader in such a structure is known as electoral stages.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Similar to procedures in ring structures, this method in each stage eliminates potential candidates until eventually one candidate node is left.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] This node becomes the leader and then notifies all other processes of termination.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] This approach can be used to achieve a complexity of O(n).
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] There also more practical approaches introduced for dealing with presence of faulty links in the network.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] A Hypercube $H_{k}$ is a network consisting of $n=2^{k}$ nodes, each with degree of k and $O(n\log n)$ edges.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] A similar electoral stages as before can be used to solve the problem of leader election.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In each stage two nodes (called duelists) compete and the winner is promoted to the next stage.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] This means in each stage only half of the duelists enter the next stage.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] This procedure continues until only one duelist is left, and it becomes the leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Once selected, it notifies all other processes.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] This algorithm requires $O(n)$ messages.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] In the case of unoriented hypercubes, a similar approach can be used but with a higher message complexity of $O(n\log \log n)$ .
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Complete networks are structures in which all processes are connected to one another, i.e., the degree of each node is n-1, n being the size of the network.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] An optimal solution with O(n) message and space complexity is known.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Passive: the initial state of processes before start.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Candidate: the status of nodes after waking up.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The candidate nodes will be considered to become the leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] There is an assumption that although a node does not know the total set of nodes in the system, it is required that in this arrangement every node knows the identifier of its single successor, which is called neighbor, and every node is known by another one.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] All processors initially start in a passive state until they are woken up.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Once the nodes are awake, they are candidates to become the leader.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Based on a priority scheme, candidate nodes collaborate in the virtual ring.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] At some point, candidates become aware of the identity of candidates that precede them in the ring.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The higher priority candidates ask the lower ones about their predecessors.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] The candidates with lower priority become dummies after replying to the candidates with higher priority.
[src:self-stabilization/leader-election] Based on this scheme, the highest priority candidate eventually knows that all nodes in the system are dummies except itself, at which point it knows it is the leader.
